+# IMPLEMENTED
+
+Smallest safe fix for Portfolio Plan Board timeline scroll drift during epic selection.
+
+- Fix applied to:
+  - `PoTool.Client/wwwroot/js/portfolioPlanBoardScrollSync.js`
+  - `PoTool.Client/Pages/Home/PortfolioPlanBoardPage.razor`
+- Build: clean (`0 Warnings, 0 Errors`)
+- Runtime validated: mock profile 1, two products, all three transition types verified
+
+# ROOT CAUSE CONFIRMED
+
+Two independent failure paths caused scroll drift:
+
+**Path 1 — `normal → selected` (Incident drift `959 → 405`):**
+
+The existing capture/restore logic ran the restore via two `requestAnimationFrame` callbacks inside `restoreSelectionLayoutScrollState`. Both rAF passes completed and correctly reasserted the captured scroll value. The browser-native focus adjustment (triggered by Blazor rendering the newly selected epic button and calling `HTMLElement.focus`) fired as a deferred layout/paint event *after* both rAF callbacks had already settled. The browser scroll then overwrote the restored position with no further corrective pass.
+
+**Path 2 — `selected → selected` (Crew drift `959 → 783`):**
+
+`PreserveSelectionLayoutScrollStateIfNeededAsync` returned early when `isSelectedLayout == willBeSelectedLayout` (both `true`). No capture or restore was issued. When the user switched to a different epic while the detail panel was already open, Blazor rendered the new selection, fired `HTMLElement.focus` on the newly active epic button, and the browser scroll adjustment went uncorrected.
+
+Evidence base: `docs/reports/2026-06-09-portfolio-scroll-writer-trace.md`
+
+# VALIDATION
+
+Runtime test — mock profile 1, `http://localhost:5292/planning/plan-board/portfolio`:
+
+| Slice | Transition | Axis | Incident | Crew | Result |
+|---|---|---:|---:|---:|---|
+| 01 | Baseline (scrolled) | 650 | 639 | 639 | — |
+| 02 | normal → selected (small epic) | 650 | 639 | 639 | ✅ no drift |
+| 03 | selected → selected (large epic) | 650 | 639 | 639 | ✅ no drift |
+| 04 | selected → normal (deselect) | 650 | 639 | 639 | ✅ no drift |
+
+Investigation trace (pre-fix, for comparison):
+
+| Transition | Axis | Incident | Crew |
+|---|---:|---:|---:|
+| Baseline | 970 | 959 | 959 |
+| After small epic select | 970 | **405** | 959 |
+| After large epic select | 970 | **405** | **783** |
+| After deselect | 970 | **405** | **783** |
+
+# FILES MODIFIED
+
+## `PoTool.Client/wwwroot/js/portfolioPlanBoardScrollSync.js`
+
+**Change:** added a `setTimeout(0)` pass after the existing double `requestAnimationFrame` in `restoreSelectionLayoutScrollState`.
+
+**Before:**
+```js
+return new Promise(function (resolve) {
+    window.requestAnimationFrame(function () {
+        applySnapshot();
+        window.requestAnimationFrame(function () {
+            applySnapshot();
+            resolve();
+        });
+    });
+});
+```
+
+**After:**
+```js
+return new Promise(function (resolve) {
+    window.requestAnimationFrame(function () {
+        applySnapshot();
+        window.requestAnimationFrame(function () {
+            applySnapshot();
+            window.setTimeout(function () {
+                applySnapshot();
+                resolve();
+            }, 0);
+        });
+    });
+});
+```
+
+**Rationale:** The `setTimeout(fn, 0)` schedules a new macrotask, which runs after the browser has completed all layout and paint work for the current frame — including any deferred focus-scroll adjustments. The third `applySnapshot()` call overwrites any browser-driven drift that occurred between the second rAF and the new macrotask boundary. The `resolve()` is deferred to the same moment, so the C# `await` completes only after the final corrective pass.
+
+## `PoTool.Client/Pages/Home/PortfolioPlanBoardPage.razor`
+
+**Change:** changed the early-return guard in `PreserveSelectionLayoutScrollStateIfNeededAsync` from `if (isSelectedLayout == willBeSelectedLayout)` to `if (!isSelectedLayout && !willBeSelectedLayout)`.
+
+**Before:**
+```csharp
+if (isSelectedLayout == willBeSelectedLayout)
+{
+    return;
+}
+```
+
+**After:**
+```csharp
+if (!isSelectedLayout && !willBeSelectedLayout)
+{
+    return;
+}
+```
+
+**Rationale:** The original guard skipped capture/restore whenever the layout mode did not change. This was correct for `normal → normal` transitions (no panel involved) but incorrectly excluded `selected → selected` transitions (panel stays open, different epic selected). The new guard preserves the skip only when neither the current nor the next state involves a selected layout, covering all three selection-involved transitions:
+
+| Transition | `isSelectedLayout` | `willBeSelectedLayout` | Old guard | New guard |
+|---|---|---|---|---|
+| normal → selected | `false` | `true` | capture/restore ✅ | capture/restore ✅ |
+| selected → selected | `true` | `true` | **skip ❌** | capture/restore ✅ |
+| selected → normal | `true` | `false` | capture/restore ✅ | capture/restore ✅ |
+| normal → normal | `false` | `false` | skip ✅ | skip ✅ |
+
+# RISKS
+
+- **`setTimeout(0)` adds a single microtask delay per selection transition.** This is perceptible only if the browser renders a visible frame between the second rAF and the macrotask. In practice the timeline retains its position visually; any intermediate paint shows the restored value from rAF2 rather than a drifted value, so the visible effect is neutral.
+- **No polling, no recurring timers, no global state.** The `setTimeout` is scoped entirely within the Promise and fires exactly once per restore call.
+- **`selected → selected` capture overhead.** An additional `captureSelectionLayoutScrollState` + `restoreSelectionLayoutScrollState` round-trip is now issued on every epic switch while the detail panel is open. This is a single synchronous DOM read followed by a double-rAF+setTimeout write, which is negligible.
+- **Regression scope.** Normal timeline scrolling (axis scroll → timeline sync via `onScroll`) is not touched. The `init` and `dispose` paths are not touched.
+
+# NEXT PROMPT CONTEXT
+
+- Root cause is confirmed and fixed.
+- Both failure paths (`normal → selected` and `selected → selected`) are resolved by the two-file change.
+- `selected → normal` path already worked before the fix and continues to work.
+- Normal scrolling is unaffected.
+- Screenshots reference: `docs/reports/assets/2026-06-09-portfolio-scroll-drift-fix/`
+  - `01-after-fix-baseline.png` — scrolled baseline, no epic selected
+  - `02-after-fix-small-epic-selected.png` — after selecting first (small) epic
+  - `03-after-fix-large-epic-selected.png` — after switching to different epic
+  - `04-after-fix-deselected.png` — after closing detail panel
+- Pre-fix evidence: `docs/reports/assets/2026-06-09-portfolio-scroll-writer-trace/`
