+# IMPLEMENTED
+
+Runtime/browser investigation completed for Portfolio Plan Board scroll drift.
+
+- Environment:
+  - API: `http://localhost:5291` (`TfsIntegration__UseMockClient=true`)
+  - Client: `http://localhost:5292`
+  - Profile: `1` (Commander Elena Marquez)
+  - Route: `/planning/plan-board/portfolio`
+- Scenario executed:
+  1. baseline
+  2. select `Emergency Alert Distribution - User Interface` (small epic)
+  3. select `Crew Location Tracking - Data Processing Pipeline` (large epic)
+  4. deselect
+- Temporary runtime instrumentation injected via Playwright `page.evaluate` only; no production files were modified for instrumentation.
+
+# RUNTIME TRACE
+
+Observed positions:
+
+- Baseline: axis `970`, Incident `959`, Crew `959`
+- After small epic select: axis `970`, Incident `405`, Crew `959`
+- After large epic select: axis `970`, Incident `405`, Crew `783`
+- After deselect: axis `970`, Incident `405`, Crew `783`
+
+Key event sequence (small epic):
+
+1. `scrollSync.captureSelectionLayoutScrollState.start/end`
+2. Blazor render triggers `HTMLElement.focus` on selected epic button (`fe.updateComponent` in stack)
+3. Timeline `scroll` event on Incident viewport with `newScrollLeft=405`
+4. `scrollSync.restoreSelectionLayoutScrollState.end`
+
+No intercepted calls to `Element.scrollTo`, `Element.scrollBy`, `Element.scrollIntoView`, or `scrollLeft` property setter were observed for the `959 -> 405` mutation.
+
+Key event sequence (large epic while details panel already open):
+
+1. `HTMLElement.focus` on selected epic button
+2. Timeline `scroll` event on Crew viewport with `newScrollLeft=783`
+3. No capture/restore calls (selected layout remained selected layout)
+
+# SCROLL MUTATION LOG
+
+| time (perf ms) | element | old scrollLeft | new scrollLeft | stack trace summary | source classification |
+|---|---|---:|---:|---|---|
+| 69230.6 | axis viewport | 970 | 970 | `scrollSync.captureSelectionLayoutScrollState.start` from Blazor JS interop | sync-module |
+| 69382.6 | selected epic button | 0 | 0 | `HTMLElement.focus` -> `fe.updateComponent` | focus |
+| 69412.0 | Incident timeline viewport | n/a | 405 | probe `scroll` listener callback | user-or-browser-scroll-event |
+| 69392.8 -> 69425.1 | axis viewport | 970 | 970 | `scrollSync.restoreSelectionLayoutScrollState.start/end` | sync-module |
+| 126248.7 | selected epic button | 0 | 0 | `HTMLElement.focus` on large epic select | focus |
+| 126253.6 | Crew timeline viewport | n/a | 783 | probe `scroll` listener callback | user-or-browser-scroll-event |
+| 145864.5 -> 145864.7 | axis viewport | 970 | 970 | deselect capture start/end | sync-module |
+| 145979.5 -> 145983.7 | axis viewport | 970 | 970 | deselect restore start/end | sync-module |
+
+Evidence files:
+
+- `docs/reports/assets/2026-06-09-portfolio-scroll-writer-trace/trace-after-small-detailed.txt`
+- `docs/reports/assets/2026-06-09-portfolio-scroll-writer-trace/trace-after-small-summary.txt`
+- `docs/reports/assets/2026-06-09-portfolio-scroll-writer-trace/trace-after-large-summary.txt`
+- `docs/reports/assets/2026-06-09-portfolio-scroll-writer-trace/trace-after-deselect-summary.txt`
+
+# STACK TRACE FINDINGS
+
+- Focus path is Blazor render-driven (`fe.updateComponent`) and occurs during epic selection transitions.
+- Scroll mutation events for Incident (`405`) and Crew (`783`) appear as timeline `scroll` events without a corresponding intercepted JS scroll writer call.
+- `restoreSelectionLayoutScrollState` executes on open/close layout-mode transitions only; it does not execute on selected-epic-to-selected-epic transitions.
+
+# CODE FINDINGS
+
+Files reviewed:
+
+- `PoTool.Client/wwwroot/js/portfolioPlanBoardScrollSync.js`
+- `PoTool.Client/Pages/Home/PortfolioPlanBoardPage.razor`
+
+Findings:
+
+- `PortfolioPlanBoardPage.OnEpicSelected` and `ClearEpicSelection` call `PreserveSelectionLayoutScrollStateIfNeededAsync`.
+- `PreserveSelectionLayoutScrollStateIfNeededAsync` returns early when layout mode is unchanged (`selected -> selected`), so no capture/restore on epic switch while panel is open.
+- Scroll sync module writes timeline scroll from axis on axis scroll and supports capture/restore APIs, but does not issue selection-specific scroll writes itself.
+- Axis remains at `970` because no axis scroll event or axis writer changes it in these transitions.
+
+# ROOT CAUSE ASSESSMENT
+
+Confirmed cause path:
+
+- **Small epic (`959 -> 405`)**: selection causes render/focus path; browser performs timeline scroll adjustment on Incident viewport (observed as timeline `scroll` event to `405`) without intercepted application JS writer call.
+- **Large epic (`959 -> 783`)**: switching selected epic while details panel is already open follows a different path (`selected -> selected`), no restore path runs, and browser scroll adjustment affects Crew timeline.
+
+Why axis stays at `970`:
+
+- Axis is not the target of the browser adjustment in this sequence, and sync module uses axis as source only; no axis mutation occurs.
+
+Why only one timeline changes at a time:
+
+- Browser adjustment targets the timeline associated with the currently focused/selected epic context, not all timelines.
+
+Why previous preservation fix failed:
+
+- The drifting event occurs in/after the selection render-focus cycle and can overwrite intended restoration for small selection.
+- For selected-to-selected switches, restoration is skipped by design (layout mode unchanged), so later timeline drift (Crew `783`) is not corrected.
+
+Answers to required questions:
+
+1. Is `scrollLeft = 405` written by application JS? **No direct JS writer observed.**
+2. Is `scrollLeft = 405` caused by browser-native adjustment without setter interception? **Yes (evidence supports this).**
+3. Does any timeline fire a `scroll` event before its `scrollLeft` changes? **No such pre-change event observed; first observable is event at changed value.**
+4. Does sync module copy scroll from wrong source? **No evidence; source remains axis.**
+5. Does restore path run too early or too late? **Effectively too early/not final; browser adjustment occurs during the same render cycle.**
+6. Does restoration get overwritten by a later event? **Yes, by later browser-driven timeline scroll event.**
+7. Are scroll listeners attached multiple times? **No evidence of duplicate attachment in this run; module disposes before init.**
+8. Are timeline elements duplicated in sync registry? **No evidence; two timelines, no duplication observed.**
+9. Does sync code use event target as source instead of axis owner? **No; sync uses axis viewport as source.**
+10. Does changing selection while panel is open follow a different path? **Yes; no capture/restore path runs for selected->selected.**
+
+# REJECTED HYPOTHESES
+
+- Timeline `scrollLeft` drift is caused by explicit calls to `scrollTo`/`scrollBy`/`scrollIntoView` in this flow. **Rejected.**
+- Axis sync module directly writes `scrollLeft=405`/`783` in this flow. **Rejected.**
+- Axis drift drives timeline drift in this sequence. **Rejected (axis stable at 970).**
+
+# RECOMMENDED FIX
+
+Smallest safe implementation (not implemented here):
+
+1. Treat browser-driven post-focus timeline adjustment as authoritative late event and add a targeted post-focus re-assert step.
+2. Run restore for both layout transitions and selected->selected epic switches (panel-open path).
+3. Re-apply per-timeline captured values after the final selection render/focus settle point, with strict scoping to selection transitions only.
+4. Keep axis as source-of-truth and avoid changing unrelated planning/mutation logic.
+
+# NEXT PROMPT CONTEXT
+
+- Root cause is browser-native timeline scroll adjustment during selection render/focus, not explicit app JS writer.
+- Incident drift (`959 -> 405`) reproduces on first select.
+- Crew drift (`959 -> 783`) reproduces on selected->selected switch because restore path is skipped.
+- Axis stays fixed (`970`) throughout this sequence.
+- No production code changes were made for this investigation.
